### Destructor

A destructor is a special member function that is automatically called when an object goes out of scope or is deleted. It is used to release resources.

---

### Syntax

```cpp
class ClassName {
public:
  ~ClassName();  // Destructor (tilde + class name)
};
```

---

### Example

```cpp
class Resource {
private:
  int* data;
public:
  Resource() {
    data = new int[100];  // Allocate resource
  }

  ~Resource() {
    delete[] data;  // Release resource
    cout << "Destructor called";
  }
};
```

---

### Destructor Rules

| Rule | Description |
|------|-------------|
| No parameters | Cannot be overloaded |
| No return type | Same as constructors |
| No exceptions | Should not throw (use `noexcept`) |
| Virtual in base | Make virtual for polymorphic classes |
| Called automatically | When object goes out of scope |

---

### Order of Destruction

1. Derived class destructor runs first
2. Base class destructor runs last
3. Members destroyed in reverse order of construction

```cpp
class Base {
  ~Base() { cout << "Base destroyed"; }
};

class Derived : public Base {
  ~Derived() { cout << "Derived destroyed"; }
};
// Output: "Derived destroyed" "Base destroyed"
```

---

### Virtual Destructor

```cpp
class Base {
public:
  virtual ~Base() {}
};

class Derived : public Base {
  ~Derived() { /* cleanup */ }
};

Base* ptr = new Derived();
delete ptr;  // Both destructors called correctly
```

---

> **Key Point:** Always make destructors `virtual` in base classes that are meant to be inherited. This ensures proper cleanup of derived class resources when deleting through a base pointer.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class MyArray {
private:
  int* arr;
  int size;

public:
  MyArray(int s) : size(s) {
    arr = new int[size];
    cout << "Array allocated" << endl;
  }

  ~MyArray() {
    delete[] arr;
    cout << "Array deallocated" << endl;
  }
};

int main() {
  MyArray nums(10);
  // Destructor called automatically when nums goes out of scope
  return 0;
}
